# 🔍 CTF Write-up: Deleted File Challenge

## 📌 Challenge Description

**Statement:**

Your cousin found a USB drive in the library this morning. He’s not very good with computers, so he’s hoping you can find the owner of this stick!

**Goal:**  
Recover the owner’s identity in the format: `firstname_lastname`.

**Provided:**  
- File: `ch39.gz`

---

## 📥 Initial Steps

First, I downloaded the provided file and uncompressed it:

```bash
gunzip ch39.gz
ls
file ch39
The file command revealed it was a tar archive inside an image file. I extracted it:

tar -xvf ch39
This produced usb.image.

🛠️ File Recovery
To recover deleted files from the image, I used foremost:

foremost -i usb.image -o recovered_file
cd recovered_file
After the recovery, the directory contained:

author.txt

png/ directory with images

📂 Inspecting Recovered Data
I first checked the text file:

cat author.txt
This gave initial clues about the owner.

Next, I inspected the images in the png/ directory using exiftool:

cd png
exiftool *.png
The metadata revealed the author’s name.

🔓 Recovering the Flag
From the metadata in exiftool, I extracted the owner’s name.
After formatting it according to the challenge requirements (firstname_lastname), the flag was obtained.

🏁 Flag
firstname_lastname
🧠 Key Takeaways
Disk images can contain hidden or deleted files recoverable with tools like foremost.

Metadata in images often contains author information — always check with exiftool.

Properly analyzing recovered files can reveal sensitive information even if the files were “deleted.”

